Introduction

  • In this current generation car has become one of the most important things in human life.

  • When we talk about a thing, automatically the first question is asked about it’s price.

  • In this project I will do Exploratory Data Analysis and Prediction of car price.

Objective

In this project my two prior objectives are

  • To do Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) .

  • To predict price of car.

Description of Dataset

  • Source : https://www.kaggle.com/code/padminisaranyakadali/carpriceprediction/notebook
  • Number of data points : 205
  • Number of Variables : 24
  • Number of Continuous Variable : 13
  • Number of Discrete Variable : 1
  • Number of Nominal Categorical Variable : 8
  • Number of Ordinal Categorical Variable : 2

Name of Variable Description
CarName Name of the car
fueltype type of fuel
aspiration aspiration type of car
doornumber number of door
carbody type of carbody
drivewheel type of drivewheel
enginelocation location of engine
wheelbase base of wheel
carlength length of car
carwidth width of car
carheight height of car
curbweight weight of curb
enginetype type of engine
cylindernumber number of cylinder
enginesize size of engine
fuelsystem type of fuelsystem
boreratio bore ratio of car
stroke stroke of car
compressionratio compression ratio of car
horsepower horsepower of car
peakrpm Maximum value of RPM of car
citympg The score a car will get on average in city conditions, with stopping and starting at lower speeds
highwaympg the average a car will get while driving on an open stretch ofroad without stopping or starting, typically at a higher speed.
price price of car

Checking Collinearity in Numerical Predictors

Transformation of Categorical Variables

  • Now we convert the categorical variables into dummy variables so that we can use it as a regression model.
  • And we delete the first column dummy set of each variable to remove multicollinearity from the new dataset.
  • After creating dummy variables we have now total 63 predictors.

Breaking the Dataset into Train Set and Test Set

  • Now I want to predict car price based on my given data.
  • So I have decided to break my dataset into train set and test set.
  • The original dataset has 205 data points.
  • The train set contains 80% of data and 20% in test set.

Model Building and Model Modification

  • Now we want to fit different model on the train set and select the best one.
  • Here,our variable of interest is price of car.

  • Clearly, the price is positively skewed.
  • So I do log transformation of price and consider that as my response variable.

  • After log transformation we can see that the skewness has been reduced.

Model 1:Considering All the Predictors

  • Here, we consider all the variables as my predictor and fit a model.

  • Here, out of 57 predictors 20 are coming to be significant.

  • They are “wheelbase”, “carlength”, “curbweight”, “enginesize”, “boreratio”, “CarName_bmw”, “CarName_dodge”, “CarName_jaguar”, “CarName_mitsubishi”, “CarName_peugeot”, “CarName_plymouth”, “aspiration_turbo”, “carbody_hardtop”, “carbody_hatchback”, “carbody_sedan”, “carbody_wagon”, “cylindernumber_five”, “fuelsystem_2bbl”, “fuelsystem_mpfi”, “fuelsystem_spdi”.

  • With Multiple R-square = 0.9858.

  • The residuals are randomly scattered.

## 168 139 
## 140 115
  • The residual quantiles coincides more or less with actual normal quantiles.

Model-2: Removing the Correlated Variables

  • Here, we remove the correlated variables and the variable “doornumber” and fit a model.
  • Here, 12 out of 49 predictors are significant.
  • The siginificant predictors are “curbweight”, “CarName_bmw”, “CarName_dodge”, “CarName_maxda”, “CarName_mitsubishi”, “CarName_plymouth”, “CarName_renault”, “CarName_toyota”, “aspiration_turbo”, “carbody_wagon”, “enginelocation_rear”, “fuelsystem_mpfi”.
  • Multiple R-sqaure = 0.9572.

  • The residuals are randomly scattered.

## 67 44 
## 55 36
  • The residual quantiles does not coincide with actual normal quantiles.

Model-3: Removing all Insignificant and Correlated Predictors

  • Here, we want to fit a model removing the correlated and insignificant predictors(obtained from Model-2).
  • Here 10 out of 12 predictors are significant.
  • The siginificant predictors are “curbweight”, “CarName_bmw”, “CarName_dodge”, “CarName_maxda”, “CarName_mitsubishi”, “CarName_toyota”, “aspiration_turbo”, “carbody_wagon”, “enginelocation_rear”, “fuelsystem_mpfi”.
  • Multiple R-square = 0.9162.

  • The residuals are randomly scattered.

##  75 108 
##  62  90
  • The residual quantiles does not coincide with actual normal quantiles at the two ends,but it coincides good in the middle portion. 

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(lm(y ~ ., train4))
## W = 0.9872, p-value = 0.1218
  • H0 is accepted and we conclude that residuals follows normal distribution.

Model-4: Lasso Regression

  • Here, we use Lasso as variable selection method.

  • Now, we want to get the value of lambda.
##  lambda.min  lambda.1se 
## 0.009039115 0.019026471
  • We will collect those variable for which the value of coefficient are non zero which is provided by lasso model by taking lambda = 0.019.

  • From the graph, we can see that just 4 predictors gives the multiple R-square 0.8 and approximately 15 predictors gives us that value 0.9.

  • Lasso provide us 18 predictors whose coefficients are non-zero.

  • The predictors are “carwidth”, “curbweight”,“enginesize”, “horsepower”, “citympg”, “CarName_audi”, “CarName_bmw”, “CarName_buick”, “CarName_mazda”, “CarName_toyota”, “carbody_hatchback”, “carbody_wagon”, “drivewheel_rwd”, “enginelocation_rear”, “cylindernumber_four”, “fuelsystem_2bbl”, “fuelsystem_mpfi”.

  • Now I fit a linear regression model where the predictors are provided by Lasso.

  • Here, Multiple R-square = 0.9463.

  • The residuals are randomly scattered.

## 168   2 
## 140   2
  • The residual quantiles coincides more or less with actual normal quantiles.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(s5)
## W = 0.99239, p-value = 0.5087
  • H0 is accepted and we conclude that residuals follows normal distribution.

Model Comparison

  • For Model-3, PRESS = 4.011418.
  • For Model-4, PRESS = 2.859928.
  • Hence, we can see that w.r.t PRESS, Model-4 is better than Model-3.
